<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Curated"><PMID Version="1">30293407</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2019</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>04</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2019</Year><Month>06</Month><Day>04</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1827-1928</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>59</Volume><Issue>5</Issue><PubDate><Year>2019</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The Journal of sports medicine and physical fitness</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Sports Med Phys Fitness</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Nutrition, hydration and ergogenic aids strategies in ultraendurance mountain events.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>791</StartPage><EndPage>797</EndPage><MedlinePgn>791-797</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.23736/S0022-4707.18.08920-X</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText Label="BACKGROUND" NlmCategory="BACKGROUND">The purpose of the present research was to analyze nutrition, hydration and ergogenic aids strategies in ultraendurance mountain events.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="METHODS" NlmCategory="METHODS">A total of 386 ultraendurance mountain races finishers were analyzed. They were divided into three groups according to their race distance: G1, distance less than 45 km (N.=250); G2, distances between 45 and 90 km (N.=71); G3, distances longer than 90 km (N.=65). The ergogenic, nutritional and hydration strategies were quantified after each race by a questionnaire.</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">We found a higher ingestion of (0.56&#xb1;0.95), caffeine (G3 203.8&#xb1;211.5 mg), water (G3 7.1&#xb1;3.7 l) and portion of sandwich (nutrition 5.3&#xb1;7.4) nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) in longer distance probes. Higher performance runners in low and medium distances consumed a significantly (P&gt;0.05) lower quantity of gels (higher 0.76&#xb1;0.98 vs. lower 1.38&#xb1;1.38), and muesli bar (higher 1.09&#xb1;1.13 vs. lower 2.04&#xb1;1.94), and in long distances higher performance consumed more water (M&#xb1;SD; higher 8.23&#xb1;3.92 vs. lower 6.12&#xb1;3.28) than lower performance ones. They also could maintain a higher rated of perceived exertion than lower performance (G3 M&#xb1;SD; higher 16.7&#xb1;2.28 vs. lower 18.2&#xb1;1.71).</AbstractText><AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">Higher distance presented higher nutritional, caffeine and NSAIDs ingestion than lower distances, also, higher performance athletes of higher distance presenter higher water and nutritional ingestion than lower performance ones. In lower distance probes, higher performance athletes presented lower hydration and nutritional ingestion than lower performance athletes.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Belinch&#xf3;n-Demiguel</LastName><ForeName>Pedro</ForeName><Initials>P</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Galapagar Health Center, Galapagar, Madrid, Spain.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Sports Sciences, European University of Madrid, Madrid, Spain.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Clemente-Su&#xe1;rez</LastName><ForeName>Vicente J</ForeName><Initials>VJ</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Faculty of Sports Sciences, European University of Madrid, Madrid, Spain - vctxente@yahoo.es.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Research Group on Culture, Education and Society, Coast University, Barranquilla, Colombia.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2018</Year><Month>10</Month><Day>01</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJournalInfo><Country>Italy</Country><MedlineTA